{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 23:14:33.564897", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and approach\n- Verified end-to-end L3 reachability from access hosts to infrastructure and server farm.\n- Checked name resolution, OSPF control-plane health, and HTTP application reachability/latency.\n- Validated policy constraints (backend servers not directly accessible from hosts).\n\nKey observations\n\n1) End-to-end IP reachability\n- From host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.11) and host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.13):\n  - ICMP reachability to server farm services is healthy with 0% loss and low RTTs:\n    - DNS 10.200.0.2, DHCP 10.200.0.8, load_balancer 10.200.0.7, web_server_[0..3] 10.200.0.[3..6].\n  - Inter-host ping succeeds across subnets (10.1.1.11 <-> 10.2.1.13), indicating core/distribution routing is working.\n\n2) Name resolution and addressing\n- Hosts received dynamic IPv4 addresses and default gateways via DHCP:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.11/24, GW 10.1.1.1 (DHCP lease active).\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.13/24, GW 10.2.1.1 (DHCP lease active).\n- resolv.conf on both hosts points to DNS 10.200.0.2.\n- getent resolves:\n  - web0..web3.local -> 10.200.0.[3..6]\n  - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7\n\n3) OSPF control-plane health\n- All FRR routers show OSPF adjacencies in Full state:\n  - Cores inter-adjacent; each core has Full neighbors on their interlinks.\n  - server_access_router has Full neighbor with core_3 on 172.16.0.14/31.\n  - Distribution routers have Full neighbors to their respective cores.\n- Routing tables are consistent:\n  - server_access_router advertises 10.200.0.0/24; learns access subnets (10.1.x/24, 10.2.x/24) via core_3.\n  - Cores learn 10.200.0.0/24 via appropriate core-to-SAR paths, and access subnets via corresponding core/dist links.\n- No indication of OSPF flaps; uptimes ~4 minutes, stable.\n\n4) HTTP application reachability and timing\n- HTTP 200 responses from all public web servers and the load balancer:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 curl to web0..web3.local: HTTP 200 with ~262 KB content.\n  - host_1_1_1_1 curl to web99.local (load balancer): HTTP 200 consistently.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 curl to web99.local: HTTP 200 consistently.\n- Timing characteristics (host_1_1_1_1):\n  - Load balancer (web99.local): TTFB ≈ 0.20–0.34 s; total ≈ ~1.0 s.\n  - Direct web servers (web0..web3.local or 10.200.0.[3..6]): TTFB typically ≈ 1.0–1.36 s; total ≈ 1.8–2.1 s.\n  - DNS lookup and TCP connect are consistently fast (< ~20 ms), so delay is after connect (server-side processing/response).\n- Backend connectivity isolation (by design):\n  - From hosts, ping to backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) fails (no route/reachability) — expected and compliant with policy.\n  - 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in OSPF (isolated behind the load balancer). The load balancer has eth1 at 20.200.0.1 with direct L2 adjacency to backend_web_0.\n\n5) Service processes\n- load_balancer: nginx listening on 0.0.0.0:80.\n- web_server_[0..3]: HTTP services are listening on 0.0.0.0:80 (python3-based servers).\n- backend_web_0: HTTP service listening on 0.0.0.0:80 (python3), reachable only on 20.200.0.0/24 from the LB.\n\nPolicy and topology conformance\n- Hosts reside in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 subnets with proper default gateways.\n- DNS/DHCP reachable across OSPF transit; routing and adjacencies consistent with the described hierarchy.\n- Backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is not reachable from user subnets, and only the load balancer has L2 adjacency to backends — aligns with “backend not directly accessible” requirement.\n\nDetected anomalies or noteworthy findings\n\nA) Elevated TTFB for direct web servers (web0..web3)\n- Symptom: TTFB ~1.0–1.36 s versus ~0.2–0.34 s via the load balancer.\n- Localization: Application servers (web_server_[0..3]).\n- Network indicators (DNS lookup, TCP connect, ICMP RTTs) are all low and consistent; there is no packet loss. The additional delay happens after TCP connect.\n- Likely root cause domain: Application/service processing on the servers (not network). The network does not appear to be introducing latency.\n\nB) Backend isolation confirmation\n- From hosts and server_access_router, 20.200.0.0/24 is not reachable; this is expected, but noted here to avoid misinterpretation as a fault. The load balancer has direct L2 access to the backend, and OSPF correctly does not advertise the backend network.\n\nC) Inventory vs. description mismatch (informational)\n- The description mentions three backend web servers behind the load balancer. The current topology shows only one backend node (backend_web_0 at 20.200.0.2). This is not a network fault; it may be a lab simplification or an incomplete backend pool configuration. Load balancer service is up and responding.\n\nConclusions\n- Overall network health is good:\n  - OSPF adjacencies are established and stable; routing is correct.\n  - DHCP and DNS services are reachable; hosts are correctly configured.\n  - Server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is reachable from user subnets; HTTP services respond with 200s.\n  - Backend isolation is enforced as designed.\n- No network-layer faults detected. The only performance issue observed (increased TTFB to web0..web3) localizes to the web application layer, not the network.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17761, "output_tokens": 5896, "total_tokens": 23657, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16128}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4416}}}
